06353nam a22013095i 9780691223940DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222001nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759401  a97806912239407 a10.1515/97806912239402doi  a(DE-B1597)574703  a(OCoLC)1312727223  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN56.M95 4aPN56.M95 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aZiolkowski, Theodore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sin of Knowledge :bAncient Themes and Modern Variations /cTheodore Ziolkowski. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (239 p.) :b7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContent -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tPrelude. The Timeless Topicality of Myth -- tPart One. Ancient Themes -- tChapter One. Adam: The Genesis of Consciousness -- tChapter Two. Prometheus: T h e Birth of Civilization -- tChapter Three. Faust: The Ambivalence of Knowledge -- tInterlude. From Mith to Modernity -- tPart Two. Modern Variations -- tChapter Four. The Secularization of Adam -- tChapter Five. The Proletarianization of Prometheus -- tChapter Six. The Americanization of Faust -- tPostlude. On the Uses and Abuses of Myth -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAdam, Prometheus, and Faust--their stories were central to the formation of Western consciousness and continue to be timely cautionary tales in an age driven by information and technology. Here Theodore Ziolkowski explores how each myth represents a response on the part of ancient Hebrew, ancient Greek, and sixteenth-century Christian culture to the problem of knowledge, particularly humankind's powerful, perennial, and sometimes unethical desire for it. This book exposes for the first time the similarities underlying these myths as well as their origins in earlier trickster legends, and considers when and why they emerged in their respective societies. It then examines the variations through which the themes have been adapted by modern writers to express their own awareness of the sin of knowledge. Each myth is shown to capture the anxiety of a society when faced with new knowledge that challenges traditional values. Ziolkowski's examples of recent appropriations of the myths are especially provocative. From Voltaire to the present, the Fall of Adam has provided an image for the emergence from childhood innocence into the consciousness of maturity. Prometheus, as the challenger of authority and the initiator of technological evil, yielded an ambivalent model for the socialist imagination of the German Democratic Republic. And finally, an America unsettled by its responsibility for the atomic bomb, and worrying that in its postwar prosperity it had betrayed its values, recognized in Faust the disturbing image of its soul.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMythology in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAdapa.  aAeschylus.  aAnacreon.  aAnaxagoras.  aApollodorus.  aBeethoven, Ludwig van.  aBerman, Marshall.  aBorrow, Anthony.  aCamerarius, Joachim.  aCleisthenes.  aDali, Salvador.  aDamn Yankees.  aDickens, Charles.  aDon Juan.  aDyson, Freeman.  aEdwards, Jonathan.  aErasmus, Desiderius.  aGreene, Graham.  aHamlet.  aHeine, Heinrich.  aHerodotus.  aHerseyjohn.  aHesiod.  aInstitoris, Heinrich.  aJerome, Saint.  aJerusalem.  aJonson, Ben.  aKeim, Andrew.  aKirsch, Rainer.  aKlinger, Max.  aKreitzer, Larry.  aKupelwieser, Leopold.  aLegenda Aurea.  aMailer, Norman.  aMainzer, Otto.  aMalleus Maleficorum.  aMelanchthon, Philipp.  aNapoleon.  aNono,